102
00:06:44,880 --> 00:06:46,240
I talked to a lot of founders.

103
00:06:46,240 --> 00:06:48,720
Some of them love it, clearly like you.

104
00:06:48,720 --> 00:06:50,479
some of them regret it.

105
00:06:50,479 --> 00:06:51,600
So let's talk about it.

106
00:06:51,600 --> 00:06:52,960
What are the pros and cons?

107
00:06:52,960 --> 00:06:53,199
>> Yeah.

108
00:06:53,199 --> 00:06:58,319
So one of the see the biggest benefit of LTD is cash infusion validation and early feedback.

109
00:06:58,319 --> 00:07:02,400
Initially when you are starting a company, when you're starting a product, you essentially have zero customers.

110
00:07:02,400 --> 00:07:05,840
You are looking for people who can use your product and give you feedback.

111
00:07:05,840 --> 00:07:07,599
Through LTD, we got both the things.

112
00:07:07,599 --> 00:07:09,280
There are like couple of downsides.

113
00:07:09,280 --> 00:07:14,880
So the biggest downside is high platform cut because in our case, Rocket Up took 40% of the revenue.

114
00:07:14,880 --> 00:07:20,639
And the second downside is we got a lot of angry customers reaching out to you for feature requests,

115
00:07:20,639 --> 00:07:23,440
for missing features, for bugs and stuff.

116
00:07:23,440 --> 00:07:26,639
And also when you launch LKD, you attract a lot of cheap customers also.

117
00:07:26,639 --> 00:07:30,240
So, so that sort of gives perception your product is not that great.

118
00:07:30,240 --> 00:07:32,880
So these are the three downsides of uh LTD.

119
00:07:32,880 --> 00:07:33,199
>> Okay.

120
00:07:33,199 --> 00:07:33,759
Interesting.

121
00:07:33,759 --> 00:07:36,479
So yeah, I mean definitely pros, definitely cons.

122
00:07:36,479 --> 00:07:38,800
What I think is cool about it is the early feedback.

123
00:07:38,800 --> 00:07:46,639
So I guess my next question would be for you is did that lifetime deal those hundreds of customers join did that actually help improve your product?

124
00:07:46,639 --> 00:07:51,199
>> Yeah definitely we had actually around more than 250 plus LTD customers.

125
00:07:51,199 --> 00:08:02,160
So there is a churn in LTD customers also the only like 10% of these customers are really going to use your product after a certain period around 20 to 25 customers they genuinely use the product every

126
00:08:02,160 --> 00:08:02,479
week.

127
00:08:02,479 --> 00:08:08,400
They used to give us very brutal feedback like because we were really new in the market they were not really polite.

128
00:08:08,400 --> 00:08:10,639
So they used to message us on intercom.

129
00:08:10,639 --> 00:08:14,319
Some of the customers were able to get our members also from internet.

130
00:08:14,319 --> 00:08:16,080
Some of these customers were really good.

131
00:08:16,080 --> 00:08:17,840
They actually helped us shape the road map.

132
00:08:17,840 --> 00:08:24,879
So they gave us a lot of good insights into content creation on LinkedIn that actually helped us improve the product massively.

133
00:08:24,879 --> 00:08:25,120
>> All right.

134
00:08:25,120 --> 00:08:29,280
Well, before we get back to Devon's story, let's talk about what he actually did.

